</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="141" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">
The specific name comes from the Latin word 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">bifidus</emphasis>
meaning split into two parts, after the form of the median lobe &quot;bifurcated apically&quot; of the aedeagus.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="141" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">
Known only from the type locality in Venezuela (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 14" captionStartId="F14" captionText="Figure 14. Distribution map of Notionotus spp." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1109.80775.figure14" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/709491" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">14</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="141" type="life history">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">Life history.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="141">
This species was collected in seepage habitats that were covered with algae and detritus (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 12" captionStartId="F12" captionText="Figure 12. Habitat of Notionotus spp. A Venezuela: Amazonas State, type locality and habitat of N. bifidus (collecting event AS- 08 - 080 b) B Venezuela: Bolivar State: Type locality and habitat of N. insignitus (collecting event AS- 08 - 058) C Guyana: Region 9: type locality and habitat of N. patamona (collecting event GY 13 - 0318 - 01 C) D Suriname: Kabalebo, habitat and type locality for N. bicolor (collecting event SR 19 - 0310 - 01 F)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.1109.80775.figure12" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/709489" pageId="0" pageNumber="141">12A</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
